 cases of human trafficking, it covered many of the sections included in the regular-migrant survey as well. The structures of the two surveys are outlined in more detail in table 2. Table\ufffd2:\ufffdMain\ufffdstructure\ufffdof\ufffdthe\ufffdtwo\ufffdsurveys The\ufffd2015\ufffdregular-migrant\ufffdsurvey The\ufffd2013\ufffdirregular-migrant\ufffdsurvey Background of the respondents Pre-departure conditions Nature of work and salary in Lao PDR, quality of life in home country, reasons for migration, previous migration experience Nature of work and salary in Lao PDR, quality of life in home country Recruitment and migration stage Reasons for choosing a recruitment agency, costs and financing of migration, contract details, pre-departure training, and journey to Thailand Reasons for migration, journey to Thailand, costs and financing of migration, anticipated job and conditions Conditions at destination Training at workplace, work and living conditions including salary and deductions, remittances, complaint mechanisms, and quality of life in Thailand Work and living conditions including salary and deductions, quality of life in Thailand, previous migration experience End of work and return to Lao PDR Arrangements and costs of journey home, engagement with institutions in Lao PDR, review of recruitment agency Leaving employment, arrest and detention, return to Lao PDR Next steps Possible claims for compensation and criminal charges Interest in assistance, knowledge on human trafficking, possible claims for compensation and criminal charges, future plans - Who was possibly trafficked The analysis in this study is generally disaggregated by gender, province of origin in the Lao People\u2019s Democratic Republic and sector of employment in Thailand (the latter only in the regular-migrant survey), depending on the section of the report. The key variables including their sample sizes are outlined in table 3. Table\ufffd3:\ufffdKey\ufffdvariables\ufffdfor\ufffddisaggregatio