ases. 38 Ministry of Labour (MOL): The Labour Protection Act B.E. 2541 (Bangkok, 1998). 39 Ministry of Labour and Social Welfare (MLSW): Guideline on Implementation of Decree on Export of Lao Workers Working Abroad No. 2417/MLSW (Vientiane, 2002). 40 There were five men and one women among these six respondents, and five worked in transport/storage whereas the sixth was engaged in a food factory. 40 Figure\ufffd39:\ufffdWorking\ufffdhours\ufffdper\ufffdday,\ufffdby\ufffdsurvey\ufffd(%) 100 80 60 40 20 0 0 2.5 0.8 0.8 0 0 0 95.2 0 0 0 0 0 0 0 0 1.6 3.2 Hours 4 5 7 6 8 9 10 11 12 14 15 16 17 18 13 Irregular (N=121) Regular (N=126) 1.7 13.2 20.7 1.7 1.7 1.7 4.1 8.3 2.5 0.8 28.1 11.6 Further, 99 per cent, or all but two, of the regular migrant workers indicated that they worked six days per week, which was only applicable to 36 per cent of the irregular migrant workers. Among the latter, the majority (i.e. 63 per cent, including 70 per cent of all men and 55 per cent of all women) worked seven days a week, as against just 1 per cent of the regular migrant workers. Figure\ufffd40:\ufffdWorking\ufffddays\ufffdper\ufffdweek,\ufffdby\ufffdsurvey\ufffd(%) Regular (N=126) Irregular (N=116) 5 Days 6 Days 7 Days 99.2 36.2 62.9 0.8 0.9 About 91 per cent of the regular migrant workers noted that their weekly working hours were the same as originally agreed. Six per cent reported having worked more, whereas 1 per cent worked less than previously agreed. Three per cent said that the question was not applicable given that the working time had not been agreed upon before. More men than women (8 per cent to 2 per cent) and more respondents from Champassack than Luang Prabang (9 per cent compared to 0 per cent) indicated that they worked longer hours than originally agreed, whereas results were consistent by type of work in Thailand. The irregular-migrant survey did not include a question of how actual working hours compared to previous agreements. It is worth pointing out that, with some exceptions, the standard daily and weekly working hours in Thailand must not exceed eight and 48 hours respectively, according to the Labour Protection Act.41 Whilst such standards were largely upheld among the regular migrant workers, the experiences of the irregular migrant workers suggest breaches in this respect. 41 Ministry of Labour (MOL): The Labour Protection Act B.E. 2541 (Bangkok, 1998). What\u2019s the incentive?", "start_char_idx": null, "end_char_idx": null, "text_template": "{metadata_str}\n\n{content}", "metadata_template": "{key}: {value}", "metadata_seperator": "\n"}, "__type__": "1"}, "14f92bfa-d190-43e3-a151-b303011c38f0": {"__data__": {"id_": "14f92bfa-d190-43e3-a151-b303011c38f0", "embedding": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/whats-incentive", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "excluded_embed_metadata_keys": [], "excluded_llm_metadata_keys": [], "relationships": {"1": {"node_id": "What's the Incentive?", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/whats-incentive", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "611a57b9f4bb1a7a40a04f81d74e3dd8fec2fabd692d4db28ef6d53c62703847"}, "2": {"node_id": "d6303f57-ac3a-454e-b991-4417a7f8ea1a", "node_type": null, "metadata": {"Title_URL": "https://www.undp.org/asia-pacific/publications/whats-incentive", "Author": "United Nations Development Programme", "Publisher": "United Nations Development Programme", "Type": "Report"}, "hash": "ea92abb3ea119beafbdaffdea96dd358a3cd925e0015d39a84e50307ac10e50e"}}, "hash": "0c6483aee25388b7eb907f0819dced06a40bebe2f559b0a1f827213f6b8b6eea", "text": "2541 (Bangkok, 1998). What\u2019s the incentive? Comparing regular and irregular migrant work experiences from the Lao People\u2019s Democratic Republic to Tha